UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=35, key_takeaways=ARRAY['Property law defines who owns what; surveying locates where that ownership lies on the ground.','Texas law is hierarchical: Constitution, statutes (codes), administrative rules (TAC), then case law.','Boundary and title disputes are civil matters that end at the Supreme Court of Texas, not the Court of Criminal Appeals.','Surveyors locate boundaries and flag conflicts; they do not render title opinions or practice law.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Explain why a land surveyor must understand the legal framework of property ownership, not merely measurement.','Identify the sources and hierarchy of Texas law and the structure of the Texas court system.','Distinguish the surveyor''s role (locating boundaries) from the attorney''s role (opining on ownership).']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='acc04b01-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='acc04b01-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=35, key_takeaways=ARRAY['Ownership is a bundle of separable rights: possess, use, exclude, transfer, and profit.','Texas presumes a conveyance passes the entire fee simple unless a lesser estate is expressly limited (§5.001).','Defeasible fees leave a future interest: a possibility of reverter or a power of termination.','Texas abolished the Rule in Shelley''s Case and the Doctrine of Worthier Title by §5.042.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Describe the bundle of rights and the principal freehold and future estates recognized in Texas.','Distinguish fee simple absolute from defeasible fees and life estates.','Explain which common-law estate rules Texas has abolished by statute (Prop. Code §5.042).']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='acc04b02-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='acc04b02-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=35, key_takeaways=ARRAY['A general warranty deed warrants against all defects; a special warranty only against the grantor''s own acts; a quitclaim conveys only whatever interest the grantor has.','Texas implied covenants (§5.023) cover only no-prior-conveyance and no-encumbrances — not that the grantor actually owns the land.','Deeds are construed by the intent expressed within the four corners, harmonizing all parts.','A Texas quitclaim grantee is generally NOT a bona fide purchaser, though §13.006 (2021) adds a four-year cleansing window for downstream purchasers.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Distinguish general warranty, special warranty, and quitclaim deeds and the warranties each carries.','Apply the Texas four-corners / intent rule when construing a deed.','Explain why a Texas quitclaim grantee is generally not a bona fide purchaser, and the 2021 §13.006 cleansing window.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='acc04b03-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='acc04b03-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=35, key_takeaways=ARRAY['A metes-and-bounds description states a Point of Beginning, runs continuous bearing-distance calls around a closed perimeter, ties to monuments, and returns to the POB.','Texas descriptions are anchored to an original GLO survey + abstract number, not a PLSS grid.','Monuments control over bearings and distances; stated area is the least reliable element.','Current standards are in 22 TAC Ch. 138, Subch. E; the old Ch. 663 was repealed and is outdated for 2026.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['List the required elements of a Texas metes-and-bounds description.','Explain the Texas convention of tying a description to the original GLO survey and abstract number.','Apply the current TBPELS standard (22 TAC Ch. 138) and avoid citing the repealed Ch. 663.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='acc04b04-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='acc04b04-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=30, key_takeaways=ARRAY['The PLSS rectangular system (township, range, section) is the federal grid used in most western states.','Texas never adopted the PLSS; it retained the Spanish/Mexican grant + abstract framework.','Lot-and-block descriptions reference a recorded subdivision plat by lot, block, subdivision name, and recording data.','Dividing a tract into a subdivision in Texas generally requires a recorded plat (Loc. Gov''t Code §212.004).']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Describe the federal PLSS township-range-section framework and why Texas does not use it.','Explain the lot-and-block (recorded-plat) description method and its use in Texas subdivisions.','Identify when a Texas metes-and-bounds split triggers the platting requirement.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='acc04b05-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='acc04b05-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=35, key_takeaways=ARRAY['Every Texas title traces to Spain, Mexico, the Republic of Texas, or the State of Texas.','Texas retained its public lands at annexation in 1845; its land was never federal public domain.','The GLO (founded 1836) is custodian of grant records and still issues patents.','The Texas vara is fixed at 33⅓ inches; a labor ≈ 177 acres and a league ≈ 4,428 acres.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Identify the four sovereigns of the soil and the instruments that severed Texas land from each.','Explain how Texas retained its public lands at annexation and the GLO''s role.','Convert among Texas surveying units: vara, labor, and league.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='acc04b06-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='acc04b06-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=40, key_takeaways=ARRAY['Dignity of calls: natural monuments > artificial monuments > (adjoinder) > course > distance > quantity.','The hierarchy always yields to the parties'' intent and the footsteps of the original surveyor (Stafford v. King).','Sequential conveyances are governed by senior/junior rights; simultaneous ones by proportionate apportionment.','A grantor cannot convey land already conveyed to a senior grantee; the junior takes the remainder.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['State the dignity-of-calls hierarchy and apply it to a conflicting description.','Explain the footsteps doctrine and the paramount rule of intent from Stafford v. King.','Distinguish sequential (senior/junior) from simultaneous (proportionate) conveyances.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='acc04b07-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='acc04b07-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=30, key_takeaways=ARRAY['The midterm covers Weeks 1–7: legal sources/courts, estates, deeds, descriptions, Texas land history, and boundary evidence.','Be able to trace a Texas chain of title to a sovereign and tie a description to an abstract number.','Be able to rank conflicting calls and explain why intent and footsteps override the mechanical hierarchy.','Remember the Texas-specific traps: §13.006 quitclaim window, §5.042 abolitions, Ch. 138 not Ch. 663.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Synthesize Weeks 1–7: sources of law, estates, deeds, legal descriptions, the Texas land system, and the priority of calls.','Apply the dignity-of-calls hierarchy and the four-corners/intent rule to scenario problems.','Self-assess readiness before advancing to retracement, water, and adverse-possession topics.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='acc04b08-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='acc04b08-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=35, key_takeaways=ARRAY['A retracement re-establishes existing boundaries; it does not create or move them.','The footsteps of the original surveyor control retracement, even over inconsistent field-note calls.','The dignity-of-calls hierarchy is invoked only when the footsteps cannot be retraced.','The GLO holds the original-grant records; original state-land boundary work requires a Licensed State Land Surveyor (LSLS).']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Distinguish an original survey from a retracement (resurvey) and state what each may and may not do.','Explain the footsteps doctrine as the governing rule of Texas retracement.','Describe the GLO''s role and the LSLS credential for original-grant boundary work.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='acc04b09-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='acc04b09-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=40, key_takeaways=ARRAY['Riparian rights border flowing watercourses; littoral rights border static bodies (lakes, the Gulf).','A Texas stream is navigable if its bed averages 30 ft in width (Nat. Res. Code §21.001(3)); the State owns navigable beds.','The boundary of a navigable Texas stream is the gradient boundary (Motl v. Boyd), not the ordinary high-water mark.','Coastal datum depends on the sovereign: Spanish/Mexican grants use mean higher high water; Anglo/Texas grants use mean high tide (Luttes).']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Distinguish riparian from littoral rights and navigable from non-navigable streams in Texas.','Explain the Texas gradient boundary method and the statutory 30-foot navigability rule.','Describe the dual coastal datum from Luttes v. State and the effect of accretion vs. avulsion.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='acc04b10-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='acc04b10-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=40, key_takeaways=ARRAY['Texas adverse possession is wholly statutory: Civ. Prac. & Rem. Code §§16.024–16.028 (3/5/10/25/25-year tracks).','The 5-year track (§16.025) requires paying taxes and a duly registered (non-quitclaim) deed; one missed year is fatal.','The 10-year track (§16.026) needs no instrument but is capped at 160 acres absent enclosure or a recorded deed.','Encroachments mature into title only through the strict statutory tracks; Texas applies acquiescence narrowly.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Identify the five Texas adverse-possession limitation tracks and their distinct elements.','Apply the correct track to a fact pattern and compute when title ripens.','Explain how Texas treats encroachments, acquiescence, and the surveyor''s role.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='acc04b11-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='acc04b11-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=38, key_takeaways=ARRAY['Express easements (written, Statute of Frauds) are the most-favored method of creation in Texas.','Easement by necessity requires unity of ownership before severance, strict necessity, and necessity at severance; it ends when the necessity ends.','Texas disfavors prescriptive easements; joint/shared use defeats the exclusivity element (Tran v. Macha).','Hamrick v. Ward channels landlocked road-access claims into necessity, not prior use.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Distinguish express, implied (prior use), necessity, and prescriptive easements in Texas.','Explain why Texas disfavors prescriptive easements and channels access claims into necessity.','Apply the unity-of-ownership and strict-necessity elements to easement scenarios.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='acc04b12-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='acc04b12-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=35, key_takeaways=ARRAY['The location of a boundary line is a question of fact for the factfinder; the surveyor supplies the evidence.','An expert surveyor must base opinions on the evidence (footsteps, monuments, record) and stay objective.','The surveyor testifies to where the boundary is; the court decides who owns the disputed land.','Thorough field notes, a defensible methodology, and the dignity-of-calls/footsteps analysis make credible testimony.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Describe the surveyor''s role and duties when testifying as an expert in a boundary dispute.','Explain that boundary location is a question of fact and how the surveyor''s evidence informs it.','Apply professional standards to the preparation and presentation of expert opinions.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='acc04b13-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='acc04b13-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=35, key_takeaways=ARRAY['Surveyor licensing flows from Occupations Code Ch. 1071; standards of practice are in 22 TAC Ch. 138 (Subch. E).','The old 22 TAC Ch. 663 was repealed and merged into Ch. 138 after the 2019 board merger — do not cite §663.','Only an RPLS (or LSLS for state land) may prepare a metes-and-bounds description and seal a survey.','TBPELS rules require honoring junior/senior rights, the record chain, and proper monumentation.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Identify the governing statute and current administrative rules for Texas surveyors.','Apply the TBPELS standards of practice (22 TAC Ch. 138) including monumentation and descriptions.','Explain the RPLS/LSLS credentials and core ethical obligations in boundary work.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='acc04b14-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='acc04b14-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=35, key_takeaways=ARRAY['Stafford v. King anchors the dignity of calls and the footsteps doctrine; both yield to intent.','Motl v. Boyd / Brainard give the gradient boundary; Luttes gives the dual coastal datum.','Tran v. Macha and Hamrick v. Ward show Texas disfavoring prescriptive easements and channeling access into necessity.','Adverse possession is statutory (§§16.024–16.028); standards are 22 TAC Ch. 138, not Ch. 663.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Recall the leading Texas boundary-law cases and the rule each establishes.','Integrate doctrines across the course into a coherent boundary-resolution framework.','Identify the Texas-specific divergences most likely to be tested on the final and the SIT exam.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='acc04b15-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='acc04b15-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=30, key_takeaways=ARRAY['The final is comprehensive across all 14 instructional weeks and is application-focused.','Reason from intent and footsteps first; apply mechanical rules only as tie-breakers.','Cite current Texas authority: §§16.024–16.028, 22 TAC Ch. 138, §13.006 — not repealed or superseded rules.','The course prepares you for the legal-principles portion of the SIT and RPLS examinations.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Demonstrate mastery of Texas surveying legal principles across the full course.','Apply integrated doctrine to novel boundary, water, easement, and adverse-possession scenarios.','Cite the correct Texas authority for each principle without relying on outdated rules.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='acc04b16-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='acc04b16-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';
  'eeee3250-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', 'Years to perfect Texas adverse possession (5-year track)', 'Years to perfect Texas adverse possession (5-year track)', 'Boundary Law — Adverse Possession', 'Texas limitation tracks', 'numeric_input', 'easy', 'A claimant has held peaceable and adverse possession of a Texas tract, cultivating and using it, paying all applicable property taxes each year, and claiming under a duly registered (non-quitclaim) deed, since {{startYear}}. Under the Texas 5-year limitation track (Civ. Prac. & Rem. Code §16.025), in what calendar year does the limitation period first ripen into perfected title?', 'startYear + 5', '{"decimals":0,"unit":"","tolerance":0.5}', '[{"name":"startYear","type":"integer","min":1996,"max":2017}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Identify the track","calculation_template":"Registered deed + taxes paid each year + use = the 5-year track (§16.025)"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Add the period","result_template":"{{startYear}} + 5 = {{_answer}}"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Because the claimant holds under a duly registered deed, uses the land, and pays taxes each year, the 5-year track (§16.025) applies. Title ripens 5 years after possession began: {{startYear}} + 5 = {{_answer}}.', 'acc00004-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', ARRAY['buildout','module-32','practice']::text[], true, 'buildout:m32');
  'eeee3250-0000-0000-0000-000000000002', 'Single-proportion correction of lot frontage in a platted block', 'Single-proportion correction of lot frontage in a platted block', 'Boundary Law — Conveyances', 'Proportionate measurement', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'A block of {{n}} lots was platted simultaneously, each with a record frontage of {{rec:f2}} ft (record total {{recTotal:f2}} ft). A resurvey between the two controlling original block-corner monuments measures an actual total of {{meas:f2}} ft. Using single proportionate measurement, what corrected frontage (ft) should each equal lot receive?', 'meas/n', '{"decimals":2,"unit":"ft","tolerance":0.05}', '[{"name":"n","type":"integer","min":4,"max":10},{"name":"rec","type":"float","min":48,"max":60,"decimals":2},{"name":"surplus","type":"float","min":-3,"max":4,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"recTotal","formula":"n*rec"},{"name":"meas","formula":"recTotal+surplus"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Record total","formula":"n × record","calculation_template":"{{n}} × {{rec:f2}} = {{recTotal:f2}} ft"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Proportion factor","calculation_template":"{{meas:f2}} ÷ {{recTotal:f2}}"},{"step_number":3,"title":"Corrected lot frontage","result_template":"{{meas:f2}} ÷ {{n}} = {{_answer}} ft"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Plat lots are created simultaneously, so the measured surplus/deficiency is distributed proportionately to record frontage. With equal record lots, each corrected frontage is the measured total divided by the number of lots: {{meas:f2}} ÷ {{n}} = {{_answer}} ft.', 'acc00004-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', ARRAY['buildout','module-32','practice']::text[], true, 'buildout:m32');
COMMIT;
SELECT 'm32 ACC SRVY 2343 — Surveying Legal Principles I: ' || (SELECT count(*) FROM lesson_blocks lb JOIN learning_lessons l ON l.id=lb.lesson_id WHERE l.module_id='acc00004-0000-0000-0000-000000000004') || ' blocks.' AS status;